  "prompt": "How do you get an ink stain out of fabric?",
  "response": "Getting an ink stain out of fabric can be tricky, but with the right approach, it\u2019s possible. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide:\n\n### 1. **Act Quickly**\n   - The faster you treat the stain, the better your chances of removing it.\n\n### 2. **Blot, Don\u2019t Rub**\n   - Use a clean cloth or paper towel to blot the stain gently. Rubbing can spread the ink and push it deeper into the fabric.\n\n### 3. **Test a Small Area**\n   - Before applying any cleaning solution, test it on an inconspicuous part of the fabric to ensure it won\u2019t cause damage or discoloration.\n\n### 4. **Use a Solvent**\n   - For most ink stains, a solvent like rubbing alcohol, hand sanitizer, or hairspray (with alcohol) works well. Apply a small amount to a clean cloth and dab the stain.\n   - For ballpoint pen ink, try using rubbing alcohol or acetone (test first to ensure it won\u2019t damage the fabric).\n\n### 5. **Blot and Rinse**\n   - Blot the stain with the solvent until the ink begins to lift. Rinse the area with cold water to remove the solvent and ink residue.\n\n### 6. **Wash the Fabric**\n   - Wash the fabric according to its care label. Use the warmest water safe for the fabric and add a laundry detergent. Avoid drying the fabric until the stain is completely gone, as heat can set the stain.\n\n### 7. **Repeat if Necessary**\n   - If the stain persists, repeat the process or try using a stain remover or laundry pre-treatment product.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n   - For ink on white fabrics, you can also try using a mixture of baking soda and water to create a paste, applying it to the stain, and letting it sit for a few minutes before rinsing.\n   - Avoid using bleach unless the fabric is white and bleach-safe, as it can weaken fibers or cause discoloration.\n\nWith patience and persistence, most ink stains can be removed or significantly lightened!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
